  "prompt": "Is money laundering a contravention of legal standards?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a serious contravention of legal standards around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money appear legitimate by disguising its true origin, often through complex transactions or business arrangements. Money laundering is illegal because it facilitates criminal activities such as drug trafficking, terrorism, fraud, and corruption by allowing criminals to profit from their crimes.\n\nMost countries have stringent laws and regulations to combat money laundering. These laws require financial institutions and other entities to implement measures to detect and report suspicious activities. Key international frameworks, such as the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, set global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorism financing (CTF) efforts.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can be severe, including substantial fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment for individuals or entities involved in such activities. Governments and law enforcement agencies work closely to identify and dismantle money laundering networks to uphold legal and financial integrity.",
